{"/service/ndnp/okhi/batch_okhi_ham_ver01/data/sn86090528/00295864667/1920111901/0601.xml":{"full_text":"L\nCHICKASHA -DAILY EXPRESS, CHICKASHA,\nOKLAHOMA,\nFRIDAY, NOVEMBER 19, 1920.\nPAGE SEVEN\nCkickasha Daily Express\nGEO. II. EVANS ...Publisher and Business Manager\nJ- EDWIN POOL Managing Editor\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF GRADY COUNTY\nHolered at the rostoffice at Chlckasha, Oklahoma, an second class\nmall matter\nCHICKASHA, OKLAHOMA. FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 19, 1920.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES Any erroneous reflection on\nOne yr. delivered by carrier $6.00 the character- of any person,\nSix months $3.00 firm or corporation and any\nThree months $1.50 misstatement which may ap-\nOne month .60 pear In the columna of the\nOne year by mall $4.00 Express will be gladly cor-\n8ix months by mail 2.00 rected upon its being brought\nThree months by mall 1.00 to the attention of the\nSingle copy .60 management.\nQlvas All The Local News B News By U. P. Wire Daily.\nj Emerson -with more\nj Jealousy than ho really possesses,\ni After houring Oscar Soagle, he gen\nerously remurked, \"Dog-gonned If ho\nI can't sing almost as well as I can.\"\nj Some compliment, we'll say.\nSlnco Mr. Chase has acquired\nstato-wlda lame as a Jazz dancer we\ncan't understand why Alvin Powell\ndoesn't sign him fur a few stunts at\nhis 'show. But perhaps the price of\nsuch talent Is too high.\nOur idea Is that it Is a case which\nconies under the Jurisdiction of the\n\"Society for Prevetlon of Cruelty to\nAnimals\" when a woman peisifltently\nholds the threat of buying a fur\ncoat over poor hubby's head.\nprofessional I and leavo tlio door open. It's empty,\nI-... 4.1...\nuui you vo uu uu a now many peo\nple'll jump In for u short drive when\nthey see It,\" Kind Words.\nOptimistic Business View\nRoger Y. JSabsoit is recognized ns one of t lie best authorities\non business. conditions in the country. As a statistician lie ranks\nsecond to none and his specialty for many years has been the study\nof commerce and industry. Any opinions which he forms are based\nupon a knowledge of cold facts and figures.\nMr. IJabson takes an optimistic view of the business outlook in\nthis country and he gives reasons for his faith in the future prosper\nit y of the nation. In giving his grounds for believing that the\nprospects are favorable, Mr. liabson points out the following facts:\nAs'-the result of the coming of national prohibition two and\none half billion dollars previously wasted in this industry yearly is\nnow available for business projects that are more useful and more\nlikely to. promote the welfare of all people.\nIn. spite of tin wide-spread opinion to the contrary, the federal\nreserve banking system has been an important factor in stabilizing\nfinancial conditions in this country.\nAdvertising is now an influential means of moulding public\nopinion This., profession has now reached such an advincd and\ns-iei.'tuic stage, in its development that it is a logical means by whic\nt h 3 pec pi of the country can be convinced 1 hat, contrary to their\npresent opinion, business is really on a firm basis and that there is\nno ennse for the present depression.\nThe argument that the falling off of our foreign trade will!\nprove ruinous is ill-founded, for such trade only constitutes 5 per\ncent of the total,' What little stoppage it will cause in this field,\ntherefore, is of little or no consequence and will have no noticeable\neffect on the general business outlook.\nRecently the standardization of manufacturing processes has\nbeen increasing with such amazing rapidity that there has been a\nconsiderable reduction in, the cost of commodities. This is a perma\nnent influence of no mean importance and should not be slighted in\nany consideration of the future of industries in general.\nAll statistics gathered recently offer overwhelming proof that\nseasonal fluctuations in production in this country are rapidly de\ncreasing. This will prove to be very beneficial as it \"will tend 'to\nmake the demands for labor more constant.\nTaxation will be radically reduced in the near future.\nRapid progress is being made iju jndustrial education with the\nresult, that the men employed in industrial plants are much better\ntrained for their tasks and are performing them with fur greater\nefficiency; The trade schools that a re ''now established in all sections\nof the country are accomplishing wonders in 1 his way.\nThe United States.' as a result of the war, is now a creditor na\ntion instead of a debtor nation, and, therefore, is in a very powerful\nposition in the business world...'\no\nFirst Meeting of League Assembly.\nDespite the information which was dispensed so freely, during\nthe recent political campaign to the effect that the League oFTCiF\ntions is dead, the general assembly of the organization is holding;\nits first, meeting at Geneva and its sessions are attracting world- j\nwide attention. The machinery of the league is in motion but it if\nadmitted that the whole movement is still a huge experiment and\nvery much depends upon the future action of the American govern-\nnient in regard to it. The editorial writer of the Dallas News, in!\ncommenting on the meeting of the assembly, says: I\nTo prevent the occurrence of war is the task and mission of the j\nLeague of Nations. Failure or success would alike be niomenloils. j\nIt were idle to speculate on the probable outcome or this experi\nment. That .has already been done to the degree that makes it\nwearisome. Yet one may be permitted to say that even though\nthe machinery should not work in the precise maimer intended by\nthose who designed it, reasoned Jiope may find rich promise in llie\nmere assemblage of the nations periodically to consider those prob\nlems and controversies which, are the inevitable incidents in the\nrelations of organized political communities. For it is these little\nproblems' and' controversies, grown big and aggravated by 4 hue,\n1 hat-become the occasions and provocations o.f most wars, so tljat\nit dies a practical 'work of 'prevention \"to bring' Iheni'uiuler moderat\ning counsel at a stage of their development which leaves the 111 sus\ncepfible' .\"Jo 'the treatment of reason. If every' other -article of ithe\nV covenant Were canceled.\" leaving, only that which calls '.the nations\ninto annual conference in fulfillment of 'tT.e soldmii promise given 'in\nt he; preamble, .the co veiling of 1 he. Assembly of the League, of Xa t ijons\nv.-ould be an event wliK'h might well' move enli,v'ite'icd men -end Vo\nmen into benisoning it with' a prayer of hope and tliauksgiving.\ni' It might be -asked, therefore, that we. shallvbe' inade-to hearj no\nmore of Ihat-raven-liUe refrain. \"The league is dead. t That croak-\niiig-song, exhausted its. service. in aidingto winan -elect ion. Toire\n'?i peat-it now.would, be-oiilvito affront the intelligence of ttiosw vlm\nSI Simp says ho notices after he\npuis on 111s neavles mar. they neve\nfeel comfortable, on a warm day.\nAs an example of a well-traiiied,\nobedient husband, we point to the\ncase of the man who goes to a dance\nwhen t';e Mrs. is out of town merely\nbecause it is wifey's wish.\nThis is the day when C. II. S.\nclashes with the Tulsa football team\nand wo don't mind confessing that\nwe'll feel relieved when the suspense\nIs over.\nliven at the risk of peeving Ed.\nwe'll have to admit that Oscar\nSeagle holds some of his notes lon\nger than we have ever been aide\nto prevail upon Friend Hanker to\nhold ours.\nAnother thing which distinguishes\nthe female of the species from the\nmale is the fact that a man can get\nout a five-year old derby and wear\nit and feel dressed up.\nHave you answered\nroll call.\nAn Unreserved Front.\nA mud-apatted doubh-boy slouched\nInto the\"Y\" hut here an entertain\nment was in progress and slumped\nInto a front seat,\nFirm, kindly, and efficient, a V.\nM. C. A. man approached him, say\ning: \"Sorry, buddy, but' the entire\nfront section is reserved f